---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Symbols" description="Public symbols of Vaelinya.">
  <section class="page-section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Artefacts</p>
    <h1>Symbols</h1>
    <p class="lede">Symbols help readers recognise identity, meaning, and repeated marks across Vaelinya.</p>
    <p>A symbol may be worn, carved, drawn, printed, or noticed in a story. It gives a visible sign a reader can recognise as the world grows deeper.</p>

    <article class="visual-callout visual-callout-artefacts">
      <div class="visual-callout-mark" aria-hidden="true"><span>Na</span></div>
      <div class="visual-callout-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">First symbol</p>
        <h2>NAVAN — Remember</h2>
        <p>NAVAN means “Remember.” It points toward truth, witness, and what should be kept alive.</p>
        <a class="visual-callout-link" href="/artefacts/symbols/navan/">Open the NAVAN symbol page</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Symbol access rule</p>
      <h2>Symbols must also be readable as text</h2>
      <p>Vaelinya symbols can be visual, but their meaning must never depend on sight alone. Every important symbol needs a plain text name, description, and world meaning.</p>
      <div class="link-list">
        <a href="/language/lexicon/">Read NAVAN in the lexicon</a>
        <a href="/world/the-warm-remembering/">Warm Remembering</a>
        <a href="/read/lina/">Lina’s stories</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <div class="link-list">
      <a href="/artefacts/maps/">Related maps</a>
      <a href="/artefacts/story-objects/">Story objects</a>
      <a href="/language/lexicon/">Words behind symbols</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
